Introduction

  • Last class we discussed about Hardy-Weiberg principles, a principle that holds true only when individuals in a population mate at random
  • Inbreeding is a form of non-random mating based on genetic relationship, since it occurs when two mating individuals have a common ancestror
  • Inbreeding increase the frequency of homozygotes, that have some consequences:
    • Deleterious alleles are more frequently in homozygotes
    • Reduce the natural
  • Genetic marker data are widely used to estimate inbreeding and relatedness between individuals in a population in which pedigree records are either lacking or unreliable.

Relatedness, Consanguinity and Inbreeding

Concepts

  • Two individuals may have a common ancestor. A simple way of measuring the degree of relatedeness between two individuals is the coefficient of relationship. That was originally proposed by Wright in 1922.
  • If they are related, both may have two received two copies of the same allele from the ancestor. Such copies are said to be identical by descent (IBD).
  • The probability that two copies of a gene are IBD is called the inbreeding coefficient (f).
  • The coefficient of relationship is intuitively atractive and conceptually clear, but it is not the most useful measure of relationship.
  • Coefficient of Consanguinity (\(r_{xy}\)) proposed by Malecot in 1948 ,is more frequent and represent the probability that two alleles, one chosen at random from each of two individuals, are IBD. It is also called kinship , coancestry, parenté or parentage.

In this course we will show that this capacity to connect individuals using pedigree records or molecular data is the statistical and genetic basis of key concepts in the Quantitative genetic area, including the prediction of breeding values and estimating heritability. A spoiler here, the reason for that is that coancestry explains an important portion of the genetic variation. Namely, the additive genetic relationship between two individuals is twice their coancestry. Just keep it in mind for the future.

Bonus

Why the \(r_{xy}\) between parent-offspring is equal to 0.25?

  • Kempthorne pg. 73
  • Assuming two individuals (X and Y) and a given locus with four alleles (a,b,c,d) as: X(a,b) and Y (c,d)
  • \(r_{XY} = \dfrac{1}{4}[P(a=c) + P(a=d) + P(b=c) + P(b=d)]\)
  • When we cross X and Y, we have the follow configurations for two siblings:
Share two aleles Share one allele Share zero alleles
ac-ac (1/16) ac-ad (2/16) ac-bd (2/16)
ad-ad (1/16) ac-bc (2/16) ad-bc (2/16)
bc-bc (1/16) ad-bd (2/16)
bd-bd (1/16) bc-bc (2/16)
4/16 8/16 4/16

S7 = \(r = 1/4 [P(a=c) + P(a=d) + P(b=c) + P(b=d)]\)
S7 = \(r = 1/4 [1+0+0+1] = \dfrac{1}{2}\)

S8 = \(r = 1/4 [P(a=c) + P(a=d) + P(b=c) + P(b=d)]\)
S8 = \(r = 1/4 [1+0+0+0] = \dfrac{1}{4}\)

S9 = \(r = 1/4 [P(a=c) + P(a=d) + P(b=c) + P(b=d)]\)
S9 = \(r = 1/4 [0+0+0+0] = 0\)

On average:

\[r = (1/2 \times 4/16) + (1/4 \times 8/16) + (0 \times 4/16) = 0.25 \]

COANCENTRY software

  • Original paper
  • Estimates of coancetry may be derived in a variety of ways.
  • So far, relatedness was presented as expected values given IBD probabilities from a known pedigree

  • Marker-based relatedness can be used for unkown pedigree and can also provide more accurate results

  • There is not one universal ‘best’ relatedness estimator, and the performance of estimators depends on the characteristics of the data
  • Maximum-likelihood estimators of relatedness are the most common in the literature

  • Common practice: compare the performance of different estimators on a given data set prior to choosing one on which to interpret results

  • Why the COANCENTRY software?
    • Advantage: There are many different methods for calculating relatedness, COANCESTRY program can estimate relatedness based on seven estimators, making it easy for users to compare the performance of each.
    • Drawback: platform specific, requiring a specific operating system (Windows operating system )
  • related: an R package for analysing pairwise relatedness from codominant molecular markers
    • The package can estimate pairwise relatedness using the same approaches as available in COANCESTRY.

Data Set and Objectives

  • In a simulated data set, check relatedness and inbreeding values in the simulated data set

Codes

Steps

  1. Download the package the original data set: Each row contains data for one individual, as columns represent alleles of SSR markers (represented in the form of molecular size, in base pairs)

  2. Simulate a data set of 800 individuals (100 parent-offspring pairs, 100 full-sib pairs, 100 half-sib pairs, and 100 unrelated pairs)

  3. coancestry calculate relatedness for all pairwise comparisons of the simulated individuals.Using help(coancestry) it is possible to observe that the package can compute seven estimators, account for genotyping errors, missing data and inbreeding, and can estimate 95% confidence intervals.

  4. simrel extract the relatedness values for the specific pairs that we generated of known relatedness.

  5. Check relatedness and inbreeding values in the simulated data set

# i) Download
library(related) # after installed the package, require the package
data("GenotypeData") # original data set
dim(GenotypeData) # 10 SSRs vs. 389
head(GenotypeData)

# ii) Simulate a data set
input = readgenotypedata(GenotypeData) # import name and freq of the SSR
input$nalleles #number of alleles per SSR
input$freqs$locus1 # freq of each allele
sim <- familysim (input$freqs, 100) # simulation 100 pairs of parent-offspring, FS,HS and unrelated 
dim(sim) # numb indiv: 100 * 4 * 2 pairs = 800
head(sim) # collumns are pairs of SSR

# iii)  Calculate Relatedness using the coancestry
help(coancestry)
output <- coancestry ( sim , wang =1) # Relatedness using wang method
str(output) #list with relatedness, inbreeding, freq

#  --- Output
head(output$relatedness) # relatedness between all pairs of individuals using wang method
head(output$inbreeding) # inbreeding per individual

# iv) Extract the relatadness result
simrel <- cleanuprvals ( output$relatedness , 100) # internal function
head(simrel) #  relatedness values for the specific pairs that we generated of known relatedness

# v) Plot the relatedness
relvalues <- simrel [ , 6]
hist(relvalues) # all individuals
label1 = rep ( "PO" , 100)
label2 =rep ( "Full" , 100)
label3 = rep ( "Half" , 100)
label4 =rep ( "Unrelated" , 100)
labels <- c ( label1 , label2 , label3 , label4 )
plot ( as.factor ( labels ) , relvalues , ylab = " Relatedness Value " , xlab = " Relatedness " )

hist(output$inbreeding$L3) # Histogram of all inbreeding values

Box plot comparing the relatedness estimates for pairs of simulated individuals of known relatedness using four estimators.

Conclusion

  • In order for the Hardy-Weiberg principle to hold , individuals in a population must mate at random.
  • Inbreeding is a form of nonrandom mating based on genetic relationship: it occur when two mating individuals have a common ancestor
  • There are different algorithms to compute inbreeding using pedigree records or molecular data
  • COANCESTRY is a contemporary software that computes these values easily
